{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:48:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:48:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17681"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17681"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,1,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80670"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10395"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17681"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65966"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10491"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80670"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPlasma proteins are critical in maintaining fluid balance between the intravascular and interstitial compartments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary determinant of blood colloid osmotic pressure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plasma fibrinogen concentration","Plasma globulin concentration","Plasma albumin concentration","Plasma prealbumin concentration","Plasma transferrin concentration"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma albumin\u003C/strong\u003E is the main determinant of blood colloid osmotic pressure due to its high concentration and molecular weight. Albumin accounts for approximately 80% of the total colloid osmotic pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy virtue of the major contribution of albumin, the other plasma proteins mentioned contribute significantly less to the total colloid osmotic pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EColloid osmotic pressure is essential for maintaining appropriate fluid distribution between the intravascular and interstitial spaces. When plasma protein levels fall, the resulting decrease in colloid osmotic pressure can lead to tissue oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colloid osmotic pressure is primarily determined by albumin which contributes about 80% of the total effect","Normal colloid osmotic pressure is crucial for maintaining fluid balance between intravascular and interstitial spaces.","A decrease in plasma proteins leads to reduced colloid osmotic pressure and tissue oedema."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","Darwish A, Lui F. Physiology, Colloid Osmotic Pressure. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541067/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65966"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17681"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/i